[[File:Caja de las ágatas de Oviedo.JPG|thumb|300px|The Agate box in the Cámara Santa (Holy Chamber) of the [[Cathedral of Oviedo]]. ]]
The '''Agate Casket of Oviedo''' ({{lang-es|Caja de las Ágatas}}, sometimes in English '''Agate Box''', "Box of Agates") is an elaborately decorated box, casket or small chest given by King [[Fruela II of Asturias]] and his wife Nunila to the [[cathedral of Oviedo|Cathedral of San Salvador]], [[Oviedo]], [[Spain]]. This masterpiece of 10th century [[Asturian art|Asturian]] gold work is kept in the [[Cámara Santa]] (Holy Chamber) treasury.

== Construction ==
It is a rectangular box made of wood of [[European Pear]], with a lid in the shape of a truncated pyramid. The [[Agate]] box is {{convert|42|cm|in}} long, {{convert|27.5|cm|in}} wide and {{convert|25|cm|in}} high. The wooden box is covered with sheets of gold forming unequal arches in which 99 large flat sections of veined [[agate]] are mounted. The gold is decorated with [[cabochon]] gemstones and [[coral]].  The top of the lid is a gold plaque with a cross and three large gems which was taken from an older piece.<ref>{{cite book| last= García de Castro Valdés| first= César| chapter= Cripta de San Leocadia| title= Arte Prerrománico de Asturias| date= 2004| publisher= Ediciones Nobel| location= Oviedo| ISBN = 84-8459-181-6}}</ref>  It is decorated with small animals in [[vitreous enamel|enamel]] in a kind of [[champlevé]] technique that is only found in one other work, the South German rear cover of the [[Lindau Gospels]], of the late 8th century, now in the [[Morgan Library]], New York.<ref>Lasko, 8-9, Plate 3</ref>

The base of the box is made of pure silver, with a cross made of [[Gemstone|gem]]s and with a carved [[tetramorph]], representing the four evangelists: the angel of [[Saint Matthew|St. Matthew]], the Lion of [[St. Mark]], the ox of [[St. Luke]] and the eagle of [[John the Evangelist|St. John]]. The inscription which describes the donation of the box to the cathedral is engraved on the basex.<ref>{{es icon }} "Caja de las Ágatas", Enciclopedia de Oviedo</ref> It reads:

{{quote|{{allcaps|SVSCEPTVM PLACIDE MANEAT HOC IN HO[NO]RE DI QVOD / OFFERVN[T] FAMVLI XPI FROILA ET NVNILO / COGNONENTO SCEMENA. HOC OPVS PERFECTVM ET CONCES/SVM EST SCG SALVATORI OVETENSIS. QVISQVIS / AVFERRE HOC DONARIA NSA PRSVMSERI FVLMINE DIVINO INTEREAT IPSE. OPERATVM EST ERA DCCCCX VIII.}}

''May this peaceful undertaking in honour of God endure, which Freula and Nunilo surnamed Jimena gave, obedient to Christ - this work was completed and yielded to the preserver of Oviedo. May he destroy any who removes this gift with divine thunder. This was done in the year 918.''}}

