{{Infobox artist | name = Sidney Riesenberg | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Sidney Harry Riesenberg | birth_date = 1885 | birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]<ref name=Smithsonian>{{cite web|title=Sidney H. Riesenberg|url=http://americanart.si.edu/collections/search/artist/?id=28233|work=Smithsonian American Art Museum|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref> | death_date = {{Death year and age|1971|1885}} | death_place = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] <ref name=Smithsonian /> | spouse = | field = {{ubl|oil painting|illustration}} | training = [[School of the Art Institute of Chicago]] | movement = | works = ''Over the Top for You'' | awards = | website = <!-- {{URL|Example.com}} --> | bgcolour = }}
'''Sidney H. Riesenberg''' (1885 – 1971) was an illustrator and artist who lived in [[Yonkers, NY]] and commuted to his studio in NYC by train. He is known, as a professional illustrator, for his posters for the [[United States Marine Corps]] and the [[Liberty bond]] programs, for his illustrations for book covers, magazines, and for oil paintings of diverse subjects. He retired from his professional work and dedicated his full-time energy to painting fine arts and teaching. He began, in 1937, spending summers in Rockport, MA, where he painted scenes of the small fishing town. He was active in the Rockport Art Association, teaching oil painting and participating in water color figure painting classes.
==Biography== Riesenberg was born in 1885 in [[Chicago]]. He was educated at the [[School of the Art Institute of Chicago]], where he was recognized for his compositions in oil.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Oliver|first=Maude I. G.|title=Recent Work at the Art Institute of Chicago|journal=The International Studio|year=1906|volume=29|page=cv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1HXpAAAAMAAJ|publisher=John Lane Company}}</ref> He moved to [[Yonkers]] in 1905 where he began his career as a professional illustrator, after a sojourn in the American west pursuing what became a lifelong interest in depicting the frontier west as was being popularized then by Zane Grey and other writers.<ref name=Spanierman>{{cite book|last=Spanierman|first=Ira|title=Art for the new collector III: re-emerging American artists|year=2004|publisher=Spanierman Gallery|location=New York, N.Y.|isbn=094593663X|page=65|url=https://books.google.com/books?ei=QKZ2UsOXAcTiyAGwjYG4DQ}}</ref> In the early 1930s, he began doing illustration work for magazines.<ref name=Spanierman /> In the 1930s and 1940s, his work was often featured at venues such as the [[National Academy of Design]] and in organizations such as the [[Allied Artists of America]].<ref name=AskArt>{{cite web|title=Sidney Harry Riesenberg|url=http://www.askart.com/askart/r/sidney_h_riesenberg/sidney_h_riesenberg.aspx|work=AskArt|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref> Riesenberg was also the vice president of the [[Yonkers Art Association]].<ref name=Yonkers>{{cite book|title=The Yonkers Art Association|year=1940|publisher=Hudson River Museum|location=Yonkers, New York|page=5|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0OytffPPXNUC}}</ref> Riensenberg died in 1971 in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
Riesenberg had a brother six years older, [[Felix Riesenberg|Felix]], with whom he was extremely close. They shared a love of creating art and adventure. In their youth, both wrote short stories in journals they kept.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
==Works== [[File:Liberty Bond - 12.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''Over the Top For You'', one of Riesenberg's WWI-era posters advertising [[liberty loans]], where a [[doughboy]] clutches the [[American flag]].]] [[File:National Jewish Welfare Board WWI poster.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A [[National Jewish Welfare Board]] World War I poster by Riesenberg, c. 1918]] Of Riesenberg's work, his contributions during [[World War I]] are well known<ref name=Heritage>{{cite book|title=Heritage Auctions Illustration Art Auction Catalog #7001|year=2008|publisher=Heritage Auctions, Inc.|isbn=1599672901|page=88|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dZXKoIc2E74C}}</ref> and he is described as "one of the greatest illustrators of the World War I era."<ref name=Marling>{{cite book|last=Marling|first=Karal Ann|title=Old Glory: Unfurling History|year=2004|publisher=Bunker Hill Publishing|isbn=1593730195|page=45|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f6G_dPGw-JcC}}</ref><ref name=Hinrichs>{{cite book|last=Hinrichs|first=Kit|last2=Delphine |first2=Hirasuna|title=Long May She Wave: A Graphic History of the American Flag|year=2013|publisher=Random House|isbn=0307816737|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSLD11AuvzMC&pg=PT321}}</ref> Riensenberg's style, it has been said, shows influences from [[Impressionism]].<ref name=AskArt />
He produced many posters for the Marines in addition to posters advertising the [[Liberty Loan]] campaign during [[World War I]]. One of Riesenberg's most well known works is his 1918 World War I-era poster, ''Over the Top for You'', which illustrates a young [[doughboy]] clutching the [[American flag]]. With its bold illustration and concise text, like many war posters of the time, ''Over the Top for You'' encouraged the public to support its military by purchasing [[liberty loans]].<ref name=Smithsonian2>{{cite web|title=Over the Top: American Posters from World War I|url=http://americanart.si.edu/exhibitions/archive/2007/posters_wwI/|work=Smithsonian American Art Museum|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=3 November 2013}}</ref> Among other posters, it was selected to display in the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]] under the exhibit, ''Over the Top: American Posters from World War I.''<ref name=Smithsonian2 /> Riesenberg also created several posters for the [[United States Navy]], one of which, titled ''Democracy's Vanguard'', illustrates Marines landing from a boat to initiate an offensive. Another illustrated uniformed soldiers raising the flag against the background of a warship.<ref name="Clark Univ">{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Louis N.|title=The war collection at Clark university library, Volume 6|year=1918|publisher=Clark University Press|location=Worcester, Massachusetts|page=46|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_zlVAAAAYAAJ}}</ref>
Riesenberg created illustrations, including covers, for many publications such as [[Boys' Life|Boys' Life Magazine]], the official monthly magazine of the Boy Scouts of America, [[Harper's]]<ref name=Burnham>{{cite book|last=Burnham|first=Robert|title=Great Comets|year=2000|publisher=Cambridge Univ. Press|location=Cambridge [u.a.]|isbn=0521646006|page=171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HkFKMksEwPcC}}</ref> and [[The Saturday Evening Post]].<ref name=AskArt /> His many thematic subjects included scenes from places he lived, historical and action scenes, portraits, as well as depicting the [[Old West]].<ref name=Carr>{{cite book|last=Carr|first=Nick|title=The western pulp hero: an investigation into the psyche of an American legend|year=1989|publisher=Starmont House|location=Mercer Island, Wash.|isbn=1557420327|page=37|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d9LCMJaOB5oC&pg=PA37|author2=Carr, compiled by Nick }}</ref><ref name=Gunnison>{{cite book|author=Frank M. Robinson & Lawrence Davidson; with technical assistance by John Gunnison|title=Pulp culture: the art of fiction magazines|year=1998|publisher=Collectors Press|location=Portland, Or.|isbn=1888054123|pages=73, 81|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mhYfL6Dn5g8C|edition=1st American}}</ref>
